- [ ] Disassemble the kernel at PC = 0x8000FF18 against the
  exact `linux-rv32-nommu` build that produced this trace
  (commit aab129b's STACKPROTECTOR-disabled build), with
  CONFIG_DEBUG_INFO + KALLSYMS, to identify the offending
  store instruction and surrounding function.
- [ ] Decide whether the bug is in our SoC's kernel-mode store
  alignment handling, our trap-entry CSR snapshot, or upstream
  binfmt_flat / nommu syscall path (less likely — Linux
  upstream is presumably tested).
- [ ] Confirm against hwsim by booting the same kernel under
  riski5-linux-hwsim with the trap PC instrumented — should
  reproduce the same mcause/mepc/mtval if the bug is in our
  RTL or the kernel itself, vs. silicon-specific if hwsim
  diverges.

## Context

Discovered while investigating the garbled output that follows
the clean `[init] hello from riski5 nommu Linux!` line in
`docs/perf/silicon-init-hello-2026-05-08.log` — the bytes that
look like noise are actually a structured trap-state dump
generated by the boot stub's `mtvec=0` re-entry handler. The
silicon boot otherwise validates correctly: kernel boots through
to userspace, /init's stage 1 prints, and only the syscall path
(stage 2 / 3) faults.

Closing tasks #54 (mstatus.MPP) and #56 (DT WARN) earlier today
established that the basic trap-entry / mode-switch / FDT-parse
machinery is sound. This stage-2 store-misaligned trap is a
NEW finding orthogonal to either of those.
